<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911209-0020</DOCNO><DOCID>911209-0020.</DOCID><HL>   Two Men Sentenced   For Insider Trading   In Business Week Case</HL><DATE>12/09/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A16</SO><CO>   MHP</CO><MS>CONSUMER CYCLICAL (CYC)</MS><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)PUBLISHING, INFORMATION SERVICES COMPANIES (PUB)SECURITIES REGULATIONS AND ENFORCEMENT (RGU)</IN><NS>INSIDER TRADING (ISD)SECURITIES REGULATION (RGU)</NS><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)NEW YORK (NY)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Two people involved in the insider-trading scheme usingadvance copies of Business Week magazine were sentenced toconfinement in their homes and three years' probation.   Benjamin B. Libera, 36 years old, a Wethersfield, Conn.,businessman, and Francis B. Sablone, 42, an Old Saybrook,Conn., attorney, were sentenced by U.S. District Judge PeterDorsey in Hartford, Conn., according to Mr. Libera's Bostonattorney, John C. McBride. He said a federal court juryrecently convicted each of the men of more than 50 counts ofinsider trading, but acquitted them of mail and wire fraudcharges.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. McBride said his client was sentenced to eight monthsof house confinement, while Mr. Sablone was sentenced to six.House confinement involves wearing an electronic anklebracelet, allowing authorities to monitor defendants forcompliance with the sentence. Each of the men also receivedthree years' probation. The Securities and ExchangeCommission is seeking disgorgement of the profit the men madeon their trades and penalties of as much as three times theprofit. Several others have already pleaded guilty in thescheme and have been sentenced.   Mr. McBride said he will appeal Mr. Libera's conviction.Mr. Sablone's attorney couldn't be reached for comment.   Messrs. Libera and Sablone were charged with participatingin a two-year scheme ending in July 1988 to trade insecurities of companies mentioned in a Business Week stockmarket column before the issue of the magazine was availableon newsstands. The SEC and federal prosecutors charged thatthey obtained unreleased copies from a Business Week printingsite. William Dillon, a former broker at the New London,Conn., office of Merrill Lynch andamp; Co. and the alleged leaderof the scheme, was convicted and has served a six-monthprison sentence. The three men, along with Mr. Dillon'smother and Mr. Libera's brother, were accused by the SEC ofmaking nearly $480,000 from the scheme.</TEXT></DOC>